To force an instalation, usually done to install a newwer package, you need to add "-Force" at the end of the commands

Install-Module oh-my-posh
Install-Module posh-git
Set-ExecutionPolicy Unrestricted
Import-Module oh-my-posh
Import-Module posh-git

I've had some issues with a command in the lines below, it seems we need PSReadLine version 2.1^ and the default in windows 10 was 2.0
for that you'll nedd to Force an instalation so that it will install the newest possible version of it

Install-Module PSReadLine

echo $profile
You'll get a file path in return, that's the file, which is executed every time we start Windows Terminal
We just need to simply add those import commands to this file.
To do that,
code $profile
This will ask you to create this file if it doesn't exist.

Paste the following commands and save the file.

### Configurações do PowerShell
### set default location
Set-Location ~/
### Importar os temas do oh-my-posh e utilizar o Star
Import-Module posh-git
Import-Module oh-my-posh
### Themes
# Set-PoshPrompt craver
Set-PoshPrompt star
### Autocomplete, keybinds e histórico de comandos
Set-PSReadlineKeyHandler -Key Tab -Function MenuComplete
Set-PSReadLineKeyHandler -Key UpArrow -Function HistorySearchBackward
Set-PSReadLineKeyHandler -Key DownArrow -Function HistorySearchForward
Set-PSReadlineOption -HistorySearchCursorMovesToEnd
### Autosugestões do PSReadline
Set-PSReadlineOption -ShowToolTips
Set-PSReadlineOption -PredictionSource History
### Chocolatey profile
$ChocolateyProfile = "$env:ChocolateyInstall\helpers\chocolateyProfile.psm1"
if (Test-Path($ChocolateyProfile)) {
  Import-Module "$ChocolateyProfile"
}
### personal function
function desktop {
  cd ~/Desktop
  Clear-Host
}
function downloads {
  cd ~/Downloads
  Clear-Host
}
function documents {
  cd ~/Documents
  Clear-Host
}
function init {
  cd C:\code
  Clear-Host
}
function home {
  cd ~/
  Clear-Host
}
